The fair value of cash and cash equivalents, short-term debt, accounts receivable-net, and accounts payable approximate
carrying value because of the short-term maturities of these instruments.
The fair value of long-term debt is estimated based on the quoted market prices for the same or similar issues. Long-term
debt is categorized within either Level 1 or Level 2 of the fair value hierarchy depending on the trading volume of the issues and
whether or not they are actively quoted in the market as opposed to traded through over-the-counter transactions. At December 31,
2019, the estimated fair value of Linde’s long-term debt portfolio was $12,375 million versus a carrying value of $12,224 million.
At December 31, 2018 the estimated fair value of Linde’s long-term debt portfolio was $13,725 million versus a carrying value of
$13,811 million. As Linde AG's assets and liabilities were measured at estimated fair value as of the merger date, differences
between the carrying value and the fair value not significant; remaining differences are attributable to interest rate increases
subsequent to when the debt was issued and relative to stated coupon rates.
